## Template F: Connecting to Shared Platform Services

These services are pre-deployed on the OCP-AI platform. Your application connects to them via internal ClusterIP DNS names. Credentials are already provisioned in each namespace via Vault/ESO.

### F.1 MinIO (S3-Compatible Object Storage)

#### Endpoints

| Environment | Internal S3 API | External S3 API | Console (Browser) |
|---|---|---|---|
| pai-dev | http://minio.pai-dev.svc.cluster.local:9000 | http://10.172.194.160:9000 | https://minio.dev.ocp-ai.calix.local |
| pai-test | http://minio.pai-test.svc.cluster.local:9000 | http://10.172.198.160:9000 | https://minio.test.ocp-ai.calix.local |
| pai-prod | http://minio.pai-prod.svc.cluster.local:9000 | http://10.172.202.160:9000 | https://minio.prod.ocp-ai.calix.local |

#### Credentials

Pre-provisioned as K8s secret `minio-credentials` in each pai-* namespace (synced from Vault via ESO). Keys: `MINIO_ROOT_USER`, `MINIO_ROOT_PASSWORD`.

To retrieve:

```bash
oc login -u kubeadmin https://api.ocp-ai.calix.local:6443 --insecure-skip-tls-verify
oc get secret minio-credentials -n pai-dev -o jsonpath='{.data.MINIO_ROOT_USER}' | base64 -d
oc get secret minio-credentials -n pai-dev -o jsonpath='{.data.MINIO_ROOT_PASSWORD}' | base64 -d
# swap pai-dev for pai-test or pai-prod as needed
```

#### Reference credentials in your Deployment

```yaml
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: <YOUR-APP-NAME>
  namespace: <YOUR-NAMESPACE>
spec:
  template:
    spec:
      containers:
        - name: <YOUR-APP-NAME>
          env:
            - name: S3_ENDPOINT
              value: "http://minio.<YOUR-NAMESPACE>.svc.cluster.local:9000"
            - name: S3_USE_SSL
              value: "false"
            - name: S3_BUCKET
              value: "<YOUR-BUCKET-NAME>"
            - name: AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID
              valueFrom:
                secretKeyRef:
                  name: minio-credentials
                  key: MINIO_ROOT_USER
            - name: AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY
              valueFrom:
                secretKeyRef:
                  name: minio-credentials
                  key: MINIO_ROOT_PASSWORD
```

#### Python (boto3) connection

```python
import boto3

s3 = boto3.client(
    "s3",
    endpoint_url=os.environ["S3_ENDPOINT"],
    aws_access_key_id=os.environ["AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID"],
    aws_secret_access_key=os.environ["AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY"],
    region_name="us-east-1",  # required by boto3, value irrelevant for MinIO
)

s3.create_bucket(Bucket="my-app-data")
s3.upload_file("model.bin", "my-app-data", "models/v1/model.bin")

response = s3.list_objects_v2(Bucket="my-app-data", Prefix="models/")
for obj in response.get("Contents", []):
    print(obj["Key"])
```

#### mc CLI (from within a pod)

```bash
mc alias set ocp-minio http://minio.pai-dev.svc.cluster.local:9000 $AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID $AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY
mc ls ocp-minio/
mc mb ocp-minio/my-app-data
mc cp model.bin ocp-minio/my-app-data/models/v1/
```

#### Things to know

- Use internal ClusterIP endpoints from pods, not LoadBalancer IPs
- LoadBalancer IPs are for external access only (admin tools, CI/CD outside cluster)
- Do not hardcode credentials -- always reference the `minio-credentials` secret
- Create your own bucket(s) -- do not use `milvus-bucket` (reserved for Milvus)
- MinIO is S3-compatible so any S3 SDK works (boto3, aws-sdk, minio-py)

